From 9602e0c3bb4a817ab53fe22d61a9b393aa4e5c6e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Keno Fischer <keno@juliahub.com>
Date: Thu, 16 Jul 2026 08:19:53 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 3/8] futex: Add ROBUST_LIST_COOKIE for PID namespace agnostic
 robust lists

The robust list exit time cleanup identifies futexes held by the exiting
task by comparing the owner part (FUTEX_TID_MASK) of the futex value
against the namespace local TID of the exiting task.

TIDs are only unique within a PID namespace. When a futex is placed in
memory shared between processes in different PID namespaces, two distinct
tasks can legitimately observe the same namespace local TID. The exit
cleanup then wrongly attributes a lock owned by task A to a dying task B,
sets FUTEX_OWNER_DIED, clears the owner field and wakes a waiter, which
corrupts the still perfectly valid lock and breaks mutual exclusion.

To make robust futexes usable across PID namespaces, allow user space to
opt into using user space managed owner identifiers (cookies) instead of
the TID:

  - Extend sys_set_robust_list() to accept an extensible list head
    variant, struct robust_list_head2, selected by handing in the
    corresponding size. The extended head carries a flags field, which
    is validated and latched at registration time, a cookie_offset
    field and a list_op_pending_cookie field; a nonzero __reserved
    field is rejected.

  - When the list head was registered with ROBUST_LIST_COOKIE, each
    queued list entry carries a 32-bit cookie at cookie_offset relative
    to the entry, analogous to futex_offset. The exit time cleanup
    compares the owner part of the futex value against the entry cookie
    instead of the exiting task TID. The entry cookie is only ever
    written by the lock owner, after acquiring the lock word and before
    queueing the entry.

  - A pending lock operation (list_op_pending) is attributed via the
    task private list_op_pending_cookie instead. The entry cookie cannot
    be used: the entry is embedded in the (potentially shared) lock and
    racing lock attempts of other tasks would overwrite each other's
    entry cookies while their respective list_op_pending is armed. The
    exit cleanup could then misattribute a lock held by a live task to a
    dying one which never acquired it, and corrupt it - the very failure
    mode this facility is supposed to eliminate. This design was
    validated with a TLA+ model (TLC finds the corruption within seconds
    when the pending op is attributed through the entry cookie).

  - On a ROBUST_LIST_COOKIE list the exit cleanup handles the pending
    operation before the queued entries: a queued entry can implement
    the lease which keeps the pending cookie allocated (e.g. a registry
    table slot held via a robust futex), and handling it first would
    release the cookie for reuse - and let the pending op's lock be
    legitimately re-acquired under the numerically identical cookie -
    while the stale pending op still carries it. The late pending
    handling would then mark the live owner's lock FUTEX_OWNER_DIED.
    The pending entry may already be linked into the list and can be
    requeued by a new owner once the pending op was handled,
    overwriting its ->next link, so the walk fetches the successor
    before handling the pending op. TID based lists keep the historical
    entries-then-pending order; a TID cannot be reused before the
    exiting task is reaped.

  - The exit cleanup does not mask the owner identifier: a cookie with
    bits outside FUTEX_TID_MASK never matches any futex value (fail
    closed instead of aliasing). The valid cookie domain
    (1..FUTEX_TID_MASK) is documented in the UAPI header and the ABI
    document. Entries carrying FUTEX_ROBUST_MOD_PI are skipped on
    cookie lists: kernel assisted priority inheritance (FUTEX_LOCK_PI)
    is not supported with cookie identifiers, as the kernel cannot
    resolve a cookie to a task.

  - set_robust_list() publishes the (head pointer, registration flags)
    pair coherently by passing the pointer through NULL, so that a
    concurrent get_robust_list() - which rereads the pointer after
    reading the flags - can never pair a head with the flags of a
    different registration, even when consecutive registrations reuse
    the same head address with different flags.

User space is responsible for assigning cookies which are unique among
all tasks sharing the futex. How such uniqueness is established (shared
memory allocation protocols, file locks, per lock reservation counters)
is intentionally left to user space.

The kernel remains oblivious to protocol violations like a zero cookie,
the same way it is oblivious to a forged TID in the futex value. The
cleanup can only ever affect memory which is reachable through the dying
task's own robust list.

sys_get_robust_list() reports the size which was used at registration
time, so debuggers and CRIU can restore the registration faithfully.

The compat variant gets the identical treatment; the compat cookie
address is computed with the same 32-bit wrapping semantics as the
futex word address.

This series was developed with the assistance of Claude (an AI
assistant by Anthropic); the author reviewed, validated and takes
responsibility for the changes.

Signed-off-by: Keno Fischer <keno@juliahub.com>
